         </item-info>
         <ce:floats>
            <ce:figure id="f0005">
               <ce:label>Fig. 1</ce:label>
               <ce:caption id="cn0005">
                  <ce:simple-para id="sp0015" view="all">Change in the concentrations of SOC and total N and C/N ratio in soil profiles under beech primeval and managed forests (means of each three forest stands, with each 12 or 4 plots analyzed per primeval and managed forest). While none of the differences between the two forest types were significant at the forest type level, several significant differences appeared at the site level between primeval and managed forest.</ce:simple-para>
               </ce:caption>
               <ce:link locator="gr1" xlink:type="simple" xlink:role="http://data.elsevier.com/vocabulary/ElsevierContentTypes/23.4" xlink:href="pii:S0378112722001578/gr1" id="lk00005"/>
            </ce:figure>
            <ce:figure id="f0010">
               <ce:label>Fig. 2</ce:label>
               <ce:caption id="cn0010">
                  <ce:simple-para id="sp0020" view="all">Percental proportion of the SOC pool and total N pool (organic layer and mineral soil to 50 cm) found in the subsoil (&lt;30 cm depth) (means ± SE of each three forest stands, with each 12 or 4 plots analyzed per primeval and managed forest). Significantly different means of primeval and managed forests are indicated by different small letters.</ce:simple-para>
               </ce:caption>
               <ce:link locator="gr2" xlink:type="simple" xlink:role="http://data.elsevier.com/vocabulary/ElsevierContentTypes/23.4" xlink:href="pii:S0378112722001578/gr2" id="lk00010"/>
            </ce:figure>
            <ce:figure id="f0015">
               <ce:label>Fig. 3</ce:label>
               <ce:caption id="cn0015">
                  <ce:simple-para id="sp0025" view="all">Soil organic carbon (left bars) and total nitrogen (right bars) in different horizons of the mineral soil to 50 cm depth and the organic layer in profiles under beech primeval and managed forests (means ± SE of each three forest stands, with each 12 or 4 plots analyzed per primeval and managed forest). Significantly different means of primeval and managed forests are indicated by different small letters (soil horizons) or capital letters (profil totals). Marginal significance (0.05 &lt; p &lt; 0.1) is indicated by letters in parentheses.</ce:simple-para>
               </ce:caption>
               <ce:link locator="gr3" xlink:type="simple" xlink:role="http://data.elsevier.com/vocabulary/ElsevierContentTypes/23.4" xlink:href="pii:S0378112722001578/gr3" id="lk00015"/>
            </ce:figure>
            <ce:figure id="f0020">
               <ce:label>Fig. 4</ce:label>
               <ce:caption id="cn0020">
                  <ce:simple-para id="sp0030" view="all">Results of a PCA analysis with the variables total SOC and total N pool (in kg m<ce:sup loc="post">−2</ce:sup>) in the total soil profiles or the subsoil (SOCprof, Nprof, SOCsub, Nsub) and the influencing factors basal area (BAlive), stem density (SDlive), wood mass volume (VOLlive), topsoil C/N ratio (CN), pH(KCl) (pH), cation exchange capacity (CEC), base saturation (BS), base cation concentration (Bconc), resin-extractable P (Presin), and location of the 6 study plots in primeval (PF) and managed forests (MF) in Kyjov (Ky), Stužica (St) and Havešová (Ha) in the ordination space.</ce:simple-para>
               </ce:caption>
               <ce:link locator="gr4" xlink:type="simple" xlink:role="http://data.elsevier.com/vocabulary/ElsevierContentTypes/23.4" xlink:href="pii:S0378112722001578/gr4" id="lk00020"/>
            </ce:figure>
            <ce:figure id="f0025">
               <ce:label>Fig. 5</ce:label>
               <ce:caption id="cn0025">
