            <ce:date-received day="16" month="1" year="2022"/>
            <ce:date-revised day="8" month="3" year="2022"/>
            <ce:date-accepted day="10" month="3" year="2022"/>
            
            <ce:abstract class="author" xml:lang="en" id="ab010" view="all"><ce:abstract-sec id="as010" view="all">
                  <ce:simple-para id="sp0010" view="all">Forest soils have been recognized as important reservoirs of older stable carbon (C) in the biosphere and thus play a key role in the global C cycle. While much research has addressed the consequences of forest conversion and forest use on soil organic carbon (SOC) stocks, some controversies remain as to whether primary forest soils store significantly more SOC than soils in managed forests. Here, we explore the effect of forest management on SOC stocks in European beech (<ce:italic>Fagus sylvatica</ce:italic>) forests through a paired-plot study in nearby primeval and managed forests in the western Carpathians, testing the hypotheses that primeval forests store significantly more SOC especially in the topsoil and that larger biomass and deadwood amounts are important drivers. The three primeval forests stored on average 15 % more SOC (∼1.8 kg C m<ce:sup loc="post">−2</ce:sup>) in the organic layers and mineral soil to 50 cm depth than the managed forests prior to harvest (difference marginally significant at p = 0.09). Contrary to expectation, the difference was significant in the subsoil (30–50 cm depth) but not in the topsoil. Consequently, the primeval forests had a greater proportion of their SOC pool located in the subsoil than the managed forests. Despite considerably larger wood biomass and deadwood amounts in the primeval forests, SOC pools were neither related to biomass nor deadwood mass. PCA and correlation analyses revealed a prominent negative effect of the availability of Ca, Mg, K and P on SOC stocks, suggesting that clear-cutting has slightly (but significantly) increased nutrient supply in the managed forests, likely stimulating soil biological activity and reducing SOC storage in comparison to the primeval forests. We conclude that the primeval forest reference is important for assessing forest management effects on SOC storage, and that a long history of management likely has significantly reduced the SOC stocks of Central European beech forests.</ce:simple-para>
               </ce:abstract-sec></ce:abstract>
            <ce:keywords class="keyword" xml:lang="en" id="kg005" view="all">
               <ce:section-title id="st015">Keywords</ce:section-title>
               <ce:keyword id="k0005">
                  <ce:text>Clear-cutting</ce:text>
               </ce:keyword>
               <ce:keyword id="k0010">
                  <ce:text>Forest biomass</ce:text>
               </ce:keyword>
               <ce:keyword id="k0015">
                  <ce:text>Forest productivity</ce:text>
               </ce:keyword>
               <ce:keyword id="k0020">
                  <ce:text>Deadwood</ce:text>
               </ce:keyword>
               <ce:keyword id="k0025">
                  <ce:text>
                     <ce:italic>Fagus sylvatica</ce:italic>
                  </ce:text>
               </ce:keyword>
               <ce:keyword id="k0030">
                  <ce:text>Slovakia</ce:text>
               </ce:keyword>
               <ce:keyword id="k0035">
                  <ce:text>SOC stocks</ce:text>
               </ce:keyword>
               <ce:keyword id="k0040">
                  <ce:text>Soil fertility</ce:text>
               </ce:keyword>
            </ce:keywords>
         </head>
         <body view="all">
            <ce:sections>
               <ce:section id="s0005" view="all">
                  <ce:label>1</ce:label>
                  <ce:section-title id="st020">Introduction</ce:section-title>
                  <ce:para id="p0025" view="all">In the context of global warming, carbon (C) sequestration has become a highly valued function of forests. Global forests are thought to store about 860 Pg C, with &gt;40 % of total organic C in terrestrial ecosystems stored in forest soils (<ce:cross-refs refid="b0150 b0305" id="r0005">IPCC 2007, Wei et al. 2014</ce:cross-refs>). Changes in the area of forested land, but also in forest structure, have therefore a large influence on the biosphere’s capacity to sequester C from the atmosphere and store it for long periods of time. Forest use is increasing globally with the ever-growing demand for wood products of an increasing human population, resulting in continued conversion of primary to secondary forests (<ce:cross-refs refid="b0130 b0065" id="r0010">Hansen et al. 2013; FAO and UNEP 2020</ce:cross-refs>) and recent increases in the timber extraction from production forests in some boreal and temperate regions of Europe, Russia and elsewhere (<ce:cross-refs refid="b0025 b0060 b0105 b0310" id="r0015">Ceccherini et al. 2020, Eurostat 2022, Global Forest Watch 2021, Wernick et al. 2021</ce:cross-refs>). Primary forest conversions and changing human impact on managed forests are likely influencing the C pools in forest biomass and soils (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0215" id="c0040">Mayer et al. 2020</ce:cross-ref>) and thus may be of relevance for policies directed at mitigating climate change through the LULUCF (Land use, land use change and forestry) sector of greenhouse gas accounting (<ce:cross-refs refid="b0225 b0145" id="r0020">Nabuurs et al. 2017, Hudiburg et al. 2019</ce:cross-refs>).</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="p0030" view="all">Despite the recognized importance of forest soils as a large reservoir of older stable C in the biosphere and a multitude of empirical and modelling studies on the consequences of forest conversion and forest use on soil organic carbon (SOC) stocks, some controversies remain as to whether primary forest soils store significantly more SOC than soils in managed forests (<ce:cross-refs refid="b0040 b0050" id="r0025">Clarke et al. 2015, Dean et al. 2017</ce:cross-refs>). Reports documenting SOC losses up to 50 % after severe disturbance such as clear-cut (e.g. <ce:cross-refs refid="b0230 b0245 b0290" id="r0030">Nave et al. 2010, Noormets et al. 2015, Vario et al. 2014</ce:cross-refs>) contrast with studies showing no C losses or even increases (e.g. <ce:cross-refs refid="b0140 b0005" id="r0035">Hopmans et al. 2005, Achat et al. 2015</ce:cross-refs>). A key question arising is whether SOC losses after harvest (or other intense disturbances) are transient and thus not detectable any more after several decades, or are lasting longer. If losses were transient, this would imply that SOC should approach a steady-state close to the pre-harvest level at the end of every rotation period. In this case, management history would not imprint on the SOC pool of mature managed forests in form of a legacy, as was suggested by <ce:cross-ref refid="b0295" id="c0045">Wäldchen et al. (2013)</ce:cross-ref> in a study in Central European beech forests differing in management history. However, most temperate forests in Europe and North America have century-long histories as secondary forests, which allow comparing different silvicultural systems but not to explore the impact of logging and forest management on SOC in a more principal way. This would require comparison with nearby primary forests, which are lacking in most regions especially of the temperate zone (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0040" id="c0050">Clarke et al. 2015</ce:cross-ref>). In fact, SOC comparisons between managed forests and nearby primary forests as a reference have rarely been conducted in the temperate forest biome so far. Examples from the temperate zone are the comparison of primeval and managed <ce:italic>Nothofagus pumilio</ce:italic> forests in Tierra del Fuego (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0300" id="c0055">Weber 2001</ce:cross-ref>), revealing a significantly reduced SOC stock in the managed stand, and of old-growth and historically logged northern hardwood forests in the eastern United States (<ce:cross-ref refid="b9000" id="c6745">Goodale and Aber, 2001</ce:cross-ref>), where SOC had fully recovered within 80–110 years after logging. Some information also exists for the tropical and boreal forest (<ce:cross-refs refid="b0030 b0270" id="r0040">Chiti et al. 2016, Simard et al. 2020</ce:cross-refs>). More studies have compared temperate managed forests and nearby unmanaged ‘natural forests’ with a management history in the past that were set aside for conservation several decades ago (e.g. <ce:cross-refs refid="b0035 b0120 b0175" id="r0045">Christophel et al. 2013, Grüneberg et al. 2013, Krueger et al. 2017</ce:cross-refs>). Since both categories are affected by logging, conclusions on the principal effect of management on SOC are difficult. It is thus not clear whether logging and thinning operations lead to permanent SOC reductions in temperate forests or not.</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="p0035" view="all">This study investigates SOC stocks in the mineral soil and organic layer in three pairs of managed and unmanaged forests of European beech (<ce:italic>Fagus sylvatica</ce:italic> L.) in eastern Central Europe in the Slovakian Carpathians and explores possible determinants of SOC accumulation, notably forest productivity and litter production, and standing aboveground biomass, deadwood and root biomass. Since the corresponding managed and unmanaged stands stocked on similar geological substrates, we were able to largely control for the influence of clay content and minerology, major determinants of SOC stabilization in soil (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0020" id="c0060">Barré et al. 2014</ce:cross-ref>), We took advantage of the fact that in eastern Slovakia, true beech primeval forests with no known human impact since several centuries (except for atmospheric deposition) do exist in direct vicinity to conventionally managed beech forests. With the paired plot approach, we were able to analyse the impact of conventional forest management on SOC stocks and to address the question, whether continued management reduces soil carbon storage in temperate forests permanently, i.e. beyond the length of a rotation period. The results should improve our understanding of forest management effects on the C sequestration potential of forest soils and the influence of forest structure on SOC stocks. The following hypotheses guided our research: (i) Primeval forests store more SOC than managed forests, (ii) the SOC difference is larger in the topsoil than the subsoil as management affects mainly the upper horizons, and (iii) a main driver of elevated SOC stocks are the higher biomass and deadwood amounts in the primeval forests. We also report soil N stocks due to their close association with SOC.</ce:para>
               </ce:section>
               <ce:section id="s0010" view="all">
                  <ce:label>2</ce:label>
                  <ce:section-title id="st025">Methods</ce:section-title>
                  <ce:section id="s0015" view="all">
                     <ce:label>2.1</ce:label>
                     <ce:section-title id="st030">Study sites and forest stands</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="p0040" view="all">The study took place in three primeval beech forests at montane elevation in the Carpathian Mountains of eastern Slovakia (48°01′ – 49°08′N, 22°01′-22°54′E), for which no major human intervention is known since several hundred years (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0165" id="c0065">Korpel 1995</ce:cross-ref>). Two of the strictly protected forests (the reserves Havešová and Stužica) are located in Poloniny National Park; the third reserve (Kyjov) is situated in the nearby Vihorlat Mountains (<ce:cross-ref refid="t0005" id="c0070">Table 1</ce:cross-ref>
                        <ce:float-anchor refid="t0005"/>). All three localities are part of the UNESCO natural World Heritage cluster “Ancient and Primeval Beech Forests of the Carpathians and Other Regions of Europe“. Human impact consists of atmospheric deposition of nitrogen and acids in the more recent past and possibly altered game densities, factors that are affecting nearly all forests of Central Europe nowadays (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0180" id="c0075">Leuschner &amp; Ellenberg 2017</ce:cross-ref>). In direct vicinity to the three primeval forests, we selected each one managed beech forest at similar bedrock, exposition and slope, so that three primeval-managed forest pairs were available. These stands were managed with a shelterwood cutting system with two subsequent cuts within 10 years at the end of the ca. 100-yr long production cycle (<ce:cross-refs refid="b0205 b0110" id="r0050">Marušák 2007, Green Report 2009</ce:cross-refs>). This silvicultural system is widespread in Slovakia and is practised in strips perpendicular to the contour lines of the slope, structuring the forest in longitudinal sections of age cohorts. As we were interested in long-term effects of clear-cut and management on SOC stocks, we chose managed stands shortly before harvest that had completed the SOC re-accumulation process during the rotation period. Due to a long period without thinning operations in the first decades after clear-cut, the even-aged stands have relatively high stem densities. All six forest stands belong to the Fagetum dentarietosum glandulosae forest community (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0210" id="c0080">Mayer 1984</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref refid="t0010" id="c0085">Table 2</ce:cross-ref>
                        <ce:float-anchor refid="t0010"/>). In the primeval forests of Havešová and Kyjov, &gt;98 % of canopy trees were beech (with a few admixed maple and ash trees), while the Stužica primeval forest contains about 10 % Silver firs (<ce:italic>Abies alba</ce:italic> Mill.). In the managed forests, 6 %, 23 % and 39 % of stems were maple (<ce:italic>Acer platanoides</ce:italic> L., <ce:italic>A. pseudoplatanus</ce:italic> L.) and ash (<ce:italic>Fraxinus excelsior</ce:italic> L.) in the Kyjov, Stužica and Havešová stands, respectively (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0095" id="c0090">Glatthorn et al. 2018</ce:cross-ref>).</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0045" view="all">Whereas the Havešová and Stužica stands are stocking on soils that formed from Carpathian flysch, i.e. acidic bedrocks consisting of silt- or clay-rich sediments, the soil of the Kyjov stand developed on pyroclastic andesite, which contains allophanes with high SOC-binding and –stabilizing potential (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0255" id="c0095">Pichler et al. 2021</ce:cross-ref>). Profile depth varied somewhat between &lt;0.50 m at some locations to about 1 m and more at others. Soil acidity was somewhat higher in the andesite-derived soils in Kyjov than in the flysch-derived soils, which is reflected in a higher base saturation of the latter (<ce:cross-ref refid="t0015" id="c0100">Table 3</ce:cross-ref>
                        <ce:float-anchor refid="t0015"/>). While stand basal area was similar in primeval and managed forests (32 – 43 m<ce:sup loc="post">2</ce:sup> ha<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup>), stem density was markedly higher in the managed stands in Havešová and Stužica, but not in Kyjov where densities were similar (<ce:cross-ref refid="t0010" id="c0105">Table 2</ce:cross-ref>). According to dendrochronological analyses, beech trees in the primeval forests had ages up to 400 years, while the trees in the managed stands were about 70-yr old in Havešová and 90–100-yr old in Stužica and Kyjov (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0095" id="c0110">Glatthorn et al. 2018</ce:cross-ref>, R. Coventry, pers. comm.). Consequently, stem diameter and tree height were lower in the managed than in the primeval forests (except for the Kyjov site).</ce:para>
                  </ce:section>
                  <ce:section id="s0020" view="all">
                     <ce:label>2.2</ce:label>
                     <ce:section-title id="st035">Soil sampling</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="p0050" view="all">In the primeval forests, rectangular grids were placed inside the forest boundaries and 40 circular plots (500 m<ce:sup loc="post">2</ce:sup>, 25.24 m in diameter) placed on the grid nodes, so that each plot was &gt;100 m distant to the forest edge. Grid spacing was 50–140 m in the six forests. These 120 plots were assigned to the three structurally defined development stages (initial, optimal, and terminal) of the forest dynamics cycle, adopting the approach of <ce:cross-ref refid="b0070" id="c0115">Feldmann et al. (2018a)</ce:cross-ref>, which uses the breast-height-diameter and tree-height distribution of all trees in the plots. We then selected each four plots per development stage in every primary forest for soil sampling, i.e. 12 plots (4 initial, 4 optimal and 4 terminal plots) in every forest. The three development stages were found to have a rather similar share in forest area (29–40% each) in the three primeval forests. Since the production forests consisted only of the mature development stage and were of smaller size, we established each 10 plots of 500 m<ce:sup loc="post">2</ce:sup> on a rectangular grid in each of them. Four plots per stand were selected by random and used for soil sampling. Soil sampling thus took place in 36 primeval forest plots (3 development stages) and 12 plots in the managed forests. To account for variable soil depths in the plots, we used 50 cm as a common standard sampling depth in all stands.</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0055" view="all">Soil sampling was conducted separately for chemical and soil textural analysis. In the plot centre, pits to 50 cm depth were dug and samples of 250 cm<ce:sup loc="post">3</ce:sup> volume were extracted with metal sampling rings in 0–10 cm, 10–20 cm, 20–30 cm and 40–50 cm depth at the two opposing sides of the pit for determining soil bulk density in the profiles (N = 2 per plot). Soil bulk density was determined by sieving the material through a 2-mm sieve, drying the sample at 105 °C for 48 h and expressing dry mass per volume (g cm<ce:sup loc="post">−3</ce:sup>). Samples for soil chemical analysis were collected with a Pürckhauer soil corer (18 mm inner diameter) to 50 cm depth at four locations per plot, that were placed at 4 m distance from the plot centre in the four main compass directions. Soil material was collected from the depth layers 0–10 cm, 10–20 cm, 20–30 cm and 40–50 cm. The organic matter on the forest floor (L, F and H layers) was collected quantitatively with a corer of 171 mm diameter directly adjacent to the mineral soil sampling. If a sampling location was closer than 1 m to a tree trunk or hit lying deadwood, it was shifted by about 0.5 m from this location. Soil samples were transferred to PE bags (or paper bags in case of the organic layer) and transported to the laboratory.</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0060" view="all">In the laboratory at Göttingen University, the pH of the fresh soil was measured for a subsample in 10 g fresh soil suspended in 25 mL deionized water (pH(H<ce:inf loc="post">2</ce:inf>O)) and also in 1 M KCl (pH(KCl)). The remaining material was sieved through a 2 mm-sieve, all larger root segments were extracted, and the material ground and dried at 70 °C for 48 h. C and N concentrations were determined by gas chromatography (vario EL III, elementar, Hanau, Germany). While all C in the organic layer was assumed to be organic carbon, inorganic C was determined in the mineral soil as the difference between gas chromatographic C analyses before and after combustion at 640 °C. The organic C content was then obtained by subtracting inorganic C content from total C content. Salt-exchangeable base cation contents were determined in the mineral soil samples by percolating 2.5 g of fresh soil with 0.2 M BaCl<ce:inf loc="post">2</ce:inf> solution. The concentration of K, Ca, Mg, Al, Fe and Mn was then determined in the solution by means of ICP-OES (Optima 3000 XL, Perkin-Elmer). The H<ce:sup loc="post">+</ce:sup> concentration at the cation exchangers was calculated from the measured pH change during the percolation process. CEC (cation exchange capacity; in μmol<ce:inf loc="post">c</ce:inf> g<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup>) was calculated by adding the charge of Ca, Mg, K, Na, Fe, Mn, Al and H<ce:sup loc="post">+</ce:sup> measured in the percolate. Base saturation is the percental share of Ca, Mg, K and Na in CEC. In case of the lower horizons (&gt;10 cm depth), the each four replicate soil samples were mixed to form a single sample for chemical analysis.</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0065" view="all">The soil organic carbon (SOC) and N data are presented as both concentrations (per dry mass) and pools per ground area for a soil profile to 50 cm depth (including the organic layer), obtained by relating the SOC and N concentration data to the corresponding soil bulk density and calculating element pools for the respective soil depth layers. The pools in the organic layer were calculated by multiplying element concentrations with the total dry mass of organic layer material.</ce:para>
                  </ce:section>
                  <ce:section id="s0025" view="all">
                     <ce:label>2.3</ce:label>
                     <ce:section-title id="st040">Stand structure and productivity</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="p0070" view="all">Stand inventories and measurement of aboveground net primary production (ANPP: coarse wood increment) were conducted in all plots by <ce:cross-ref refid="b0095" id="c0120">Glatthorn et al. (2018)</ce:cross-ref>, litterfall measurements were conducted at the nodes of the grid laid across the stands. Briefly, diameter at breast height (dbh) was measured for all trees &gt;7 cm dbh and tree height for subsamples of trees. Specific allometric equations established for European beech (<ce:cross-refs refid="b0260 b0315" id="r0055">Ruiz-Peinado et al. 2011, Wutzler et al. 2008</ce:cross-refs>) were used to estimate aboveground woody biomass (without foliage) from dbh, height and wood density. Wood biomass increment was recorded in the years 2014 and 2015 by repeated reading of permanently installed dendrometer tapes with a precision of 0.1 mm (type D1, UMS, Munich, Germany). The annual production of leaves and fruits was measured with litter traps with a circular opening of 60 cm in diameter (2826 cm<ce:sup loc="post">2</ce:sup>). As we assumed a higher heterogeneity of litter fall in the primeval forests, we set up 30 traps in each primeval forest and 10 traps in each managed forest on the nodes of the regular grid. Litter was collected from traps in December 2013–2015 and total surface area and dry mass of the leaf material determined (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0095" id="c0125">Glatthorn et al. 2018</ce:cross-ref>). The dbh data were further used to assign plots to three different forest development stages, i.e. initial, optimal and terminal stage, following the concept introduced by <ce:cross-ref refid="b0070" id="c0130">Feldmann et al. (2018a)</ce:cross-ref>. Briefly, all trees in the plots were assigned to the three diameter classes 7–39 cm, 40–69 cm, and &gt;70 cm. The relative importance of trees of these three diameter classes in a plot was quantified through their abundance in terms of stem number and basal area to account for tree size differences. Based on this data, the Forest Development Stage Index was calculated for the three different stages in a plot as the summed quotients of actual tree number to potential maximal tree number (the highest value reached in any of the plots), and of actual basal area to potential maximum basal area (the maximum reached in any of the plots). The stage with the highest index value in that plot was then used to characterize the dominant development stage in the plot.</ce:para>
                  </ce:section>
                  <ce:section id="s0030" view="all">
                     <ce:label>2.4</ce:label>
                     <ce:section-title id="st045">Statistical analysis</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="p0075" view="all">All calculations were conducted with SAS software (SAS Institute, Cary, NC, USA). The Shapiro-Wilk test was used to check for the probability of fit to normal distribution. Since most data sets were non-normally distributed, we tested with a non-parametric Mann-Whitney <ce:italic>U</ce:italic> test for significant differences between means of primary and managed forests, averaging over the plots of a forest to obtain means of each of the six forests. The relationship between SOC pool in the profile and selected soil chemical factors was analysed with linear and non-linear regression analyses using the software Xact (SciLab, Hamburg, Germany). Significance was determined in most tests at p &lt; 0.05. Marginally significant differences (0.1 &gt; p &gt; 0.05) are indicated in a few cases as well.</ce:para>
                  </ce:section>
               </ce:section>
               <ce:section id="s0035" view="all">
                  <ce:label>3</ce:label>
                  <ce:section-title id="st050">Results</ce:section-title>
                  <ce:section id="s0040" view="all">
                     <ce:label>3.1</ce:label>
                     <ce:section-title id="st055">Stand structural and soil chemical differences between primeval and managed forests</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="p0080" view="all">The each three primeval and managed beech forests were very similar in terms of stand basal area (35.7 vs. 36.3 m<ce:sup loc="post">2</ce:sup> ha<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup>) and aboveground net primary productivity (10.0 vs. 9.9 Mg dm ha<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup> yr<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup>), but stem density was on average roughly twofold higher in the managed forests (except for the Kyjov site). The primeval forests had a by 20 % larger aboveground biomass (386 vs. 320 Mg dm ha<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup>), while deadwood amount was&gt;4 times larger (<ce:cross-ref refid="t0010" id="c0135">Table 2</ce:cross-ref>). The managed forests differed from the primeval forests by a slightly higher soil pH (about 0.2–0.3 units for pH(H<ce:inf loc="post">2</ce:inf>O) and roughly 0.1 unit for pH(KCl); differences mostly significant), a 30–80 % higher resin-exchangeable P concentration (differences partly significant), and an about two times higher base saturation and base cation concentrations in the profile (differences significant at 0–30 cm; <ce:cross-ref refid="t0015" id="c0140">Table 3</ce:cross-ref>). Cation exchange capacity did not differ significantly between the two forest types (except for the 10–20 cm layer), but varied with bedrock type.</ce:para>
                  </ce:section>
                  <ce:section id="s0045" view="all">
                     <ce:label>3.2</ce:label>
                     <ce:section-title id="st060">SOC and N pool differences between primeval and managed forests</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="p0085" view="all">The concentration of soil organic carbon (SOC) was (averaged over the each three stands) by 4–9 mg g<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup> higher in the primeval than the managed forests, but the difference was not significant (<ce:cross-ref refid="f0005" id="c0145">Fig. 1</ce:cross-ref>
                        <ce:float-anchor refid="f0005"/>A). Due to only minor differences in soil N concentrations, soil C/N ratio was by 2–3 g g<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup> wider in the profiles under the primeval forests (<ce:cross-ref refid="f0005" id="c0150">Fig. 1</ce:cross-ref>B and C). While the SOC concentrations in the subsoil (30–50 cm) were on average significantly higher under the primeval forests, no differences existed in the topsoil and the organic layers (<ce:cross-ref refid="f0005" id="c0155">Fig. 1</ce:cross-ref>A). As a consequence, the primeval forests held a larger portion of the SOC pool in their subsoil (30–50 cm) (18 % of the profile total) than the managed forests (12 %; <ce:cross-ref refid="f0010" id="c0160">Fig. 2</ce:cross-ref>
                        <ce:float-anchor refid="f0010"/>). The primeval forests had on average a 15.3 % larger SOC pool (0–50 cm mineral soil and organic layer) than the managed forests (means of 13.3 vs. 11.5 kg m<ce:sup loc="post">−2</ce:sup>; difference marginally significant at p = 0.09; <ce:cross-ref refid="f0015" id="c0165">Fig. 3</ce:cross-ref>
                        <ce:float-anchor refid="f0015"/>). Significantly larger SOC pools in the primeval forests were found at the sites Kyjov and Stužica, but not at Havešová with far lower SOC pools in general (Table S1). In fact, the andesite-derived soils in Kyjov had roughly twice as large SOC stocks as the soils developed in sand- or claystone (Carpathian flysch) in Stužica and in Havešová (Table S1 in the Appendix).</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0090" view="all">The primeval forests tended to have larger soil N pools than the managed forests, but the difference was not significant (0.92 vs. 0.68 kg m<ce:sup loc="post">−2</ce:sup>; <ce:cross-ref refid="f0015" id="c0175">Fig. 3</ce:cross-ref>). The very low SOC pools in Havešová are reflected in the small total N pools (Table S1). As for the SOC pool, a larger portion of the total N pool was contained in the subsoil (30–50 cm) in the primeval forests (21 % of the profile total) than in the managed forests (13 %; <ce:cross-ref refid="f0010" id="c0180">Fig. 2</ce:cross-ref>).</ce:para>
                  </ce:section>
                  <ce:section id="s0050" view="all">
                     <ce:label>3.3</ce:label>
                     <ce:section-title id="st065">Determinants of soil C and N storage</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="p0095" view="all">The PCA, which was run with three stand structural and six soil chemical variables, showed a close negative association of parameters indicating soil fertility (topsoil pH, base saturation and base cation concentration, resin-exchangeable P) with the profile totals of SOC and soil N. In other words, SOC storage increased towards nutrient-poorer soils, and this relation was closer for the subsoil SOC and N pools than for the profile totals (<ce:cross-ref refid="f0020" id="c0170">Fig. 4</ce:cross-ref>
                        <ce:float-anchor refid="f0020"/>, <ce:cross-ref refid="t0020" id="c0185">Table 4</ce:cross-ref>
                        <ce:float-anchor refid="t0020"/>). In bivariate relationships, however, the negative effects of soil N, P and base cations on the SOC pool were only visible for the group of managed forests, but not in the primeval forests (<ce:cross-ref refid="f0025" id="c0190">Fig. 5</ce:cross-ref>
                        <ce:float-anchor refid="f0025"/>a - f). A negative nutrient availability – SOC stock relationship was only evident for base saturation at the cation exchangers in the topsoil, with a marked SOC pool size increase at base saturations &lt;20 % (<ce:cross-ref refid="f0025" id="c0195">Fig. 5</ce:cross-ref> g and h). This is in agreement with the PCA results that demonstrate a close negative association of topsoil base saturation and base cation concentrations with SOC pools (<ce:cross-ref refid="t0020" id="c0200">Table 4</ce:cross-ref>).</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0100" view="all">Stand structural properties had no significant effect on SOC storage. In contrast to our expectation, neither deadwood volume nor the volume of live aboveground biomass correlated with SOC pool size (Fig. A1), and we found no significant difference in SOC stocks between initial, optimal and terminal forest development stages in the primeval forests (Fig. A2).</ce:para>
                  </ce:section>
               </ce:section>
               <ce:section id="s0055" view="all">
                  <ce:label>4</ce:label>
                  <ce:section-title id="st070">Discussion</ce:section-title>
                  <ce:section id="s0060" view="all">
                     <ce:label>4.1</ce:label>
                     <ce:section-title id="st075">Do primeval forests store more SOC than managed forests at the end of the rotation period?</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="p0105" view="all">The direct comparison of nearby primeval and managed beech forests provides some evidence in support of the assumption that temperate primeval forests store larger SOC stocks than managed forests on similar soil. Averaged over all sites, the stocks to 50 cm depth (including organic layer) are 15 % higher in the primeval forests, with the difference to managed forests being significant in the subsoil but not in the topsoil, supporting our first hypothesis but contradicting the second. A possible explanation of this pattern is that the soil temperature increase after harvest extended to 50 cm or deeper, enhancing soil microbial activity and related respirative C losses also in the subsoil. Microbial activity might have been stimulated also through priming effects of fresh C inputs from dying roots and harvest debris that was transported to deeper layers with enhanced DOC fluxes due to reduced transpiration (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0085" id="c0205">Fontaine et al. 2007</ce:cross-ref>). In agreement with our results, SOC losses caused by forest management have been found to be larger in the subsoil than the topsoil in north-west American Douglas fir forests (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0115" id="c0210">Gross et al. 2018</ce:cross-ref>) and Central European beech, pine and oak forests (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0235" id="c0215">Nitsch et al. 2018</ce:cross-ref>). Seventy to 100 years of post-harvest forest development apparently were not long enough for full SOC recovery in the subsoil. The topsoil, in contrast, showed in our stands on average no reduced SOC stocks at the end of the production cycle in comparison to the primeval forests, suggesting that the rotation period was sufficiently long to enable full carbon stock recovery in the topsoil of the managed forests, i.e. a faster response of the upper soil layers, as has been observed in other studies (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0155" id="c0220">James and Harrison 2016</ce:cross-ref>).</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0110" view="all">The Havešová primeval forest on sand/claystone differed from the other two sites in that SOC concentrations were exceptionally low, likely due to poverty of C-binding minerals, as detected in a cross-regional SOC study in European beech primeval forests (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0255" id="c0225">Pichler et al. 2021</ce:cross-ref>). At this site, the SOC stock of the primeval forest was not higher than in the managed forest. We speculate that the very low SOC stocks of only 7.7 kg m<ce:sup loc="post">−2</ce:sup> to 50 cm depth at Havešová may have contributed to this result. The N stocks in the soil profiles were on average 35 % larger in the primeval forests (difference not significant), which can largely be attributed to the higher SOC stocks, as SOC accumulation with forest development promotes N retention in the soil (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0190" id="c0230">Lewis et al. 2014</ce:cross-ref>).</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0115" view="all">Since the managed beech forests of our study were about 70–100 years old with roughly 10 years left to final harvest, it is safe to assume that they nearly had approached peak SOC stocks within the production cycle following clear-cut. Thus, a comparison of primeval and managed forests on the landscape scale must find an even larger SOC difference between the two systems, as younger managed stands should hold lower SOC stocks than older ones due to the decade-long SOC re-accumulation process after clear-cut (<ce:cross-refs refid="b0155 b0050" id="r0060">James &amp; Harrison 2016; Dean et al. 2017</ce:cross-refs>). From the on average 15 % larger primeval forest SOC stock, we draw the conclusion that significant C sequestration in the soils of these Slovakian forests must occur also beyond the 100-year interval of a production cycle, if management were abandoned. In fact, the mean SOC difference of 1.8 kg m<ce:sup loc="post">−2</ce:sup> between primeval and managed forests points at potential SOC accumulation continuing well beyond the end of a rotation period, and SOC saturation in the entire profile apparently is not achieved within 100 years in the eastern Slovakian beech forest region. The few existing chronosequence studies in temperate broadleaf old-growth forests indicate a SOC accumulation rate of typically &lt;10 g C m<ce:sup loc="post">−2</ce:sup> yr<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup> at forest ages of 100–200 years, whereas repeated soil inventories yield higher rates (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0100" id="c0235">Gleixner et al. 2009</ce:cross-ref>). Assuming mean accumulation rates of 10 or even 20 g C m<ce:sup loc="post">−2</ce:sup> yr<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup> would suggest that another 180 or 90 years after the end of the rotation period are required to reach the SOC stocks observed in the primeval forests. This would support the assumption that old-growth forests can accumulate soil carbon for centuries, if large disturbances were absent (<ce:cross-refs refid="b0195 b0125 b0200" id="r0065">Luyssaert et al. 2008; Gundersen et al., 2021; Luyssaert et al. 2021</ce:cross-refs>). From repeated soil sampling in a strict beech forest reserve in Denmark, <ce:cross-ref refid="b0240" id="c0240">Nord-Larsen et al. (2019)</ce:cross-ref> concluded that SOC stocks had reached a steady-state at around 200 years after abandonment, which agrees with our findings.</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0120" view="all">Our investigation is among the very few forest SOC studies in the temperate zone that use true primeval forests as a reference. More frequent are comparisons between managed and so-called ‘natural forests’, i.e. former managed forests set aside some decades ago for conservation purposes. Some of these studies concluded that the time since management abandonment is usually too short to detect SOC differences between managed and unmanaged forests (e.g. <ce:cross-ref refid="b0175" id="c0245">Krueger et al. 2017</ce:cross-ref>). This conclusion is consistent with our assumption of a century-long period likely required for full SOC recovery after clear-cut. The legacy of forest management must thus persist in the SOC stock for considerably longer than a production cycle does last (<ce:cross-refs refid="b0185 b0235" id="r0070">Leuschner et al. 2013, Nitsch et al. 2018</ce:cross-refs>). Contradicting conclusions were drawn by <ce:cross-refs refid="b0295 b0120" id="r0075">Wäldchen et al. (2012) and Grüneberg et al. (2013)</ce:cross-refs> who compared the SOC stocks of differently managed German beech forests and found no evidence for the impact of management activities that took place more than about 80 years ago. Our results may suggest that the long management history of nearly all Central European forests often hinders the detection of legacy effects, unless true primeval forests are used as a reference.</ce:para>
                  </ce:section>
                  <ce:section id="s0065" view="all">
                     <ce:label>4.2</ce:label>
                     <ce:section-title id="st080">Factors promoting SOC storage in primeval forests</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="p0125" view="all">Three factors could in theory cause higher SOC storage in primeval forests, (i) longer periods without large-scale disturbances that enable continued SOC accumulation, (ii) a higher carbon supply rate due to higher stand productivity or larger stocks of live and dead wood, and (iii) specific SOC-stabilizing soil conditions that result from the specific stand structure and disturbance regime of primeval forests. Demographic studies in old-growth beech forests in the Carpathians have shown that natural large-scale disturbance events leading to the break-down of whole stands are very rare in central and south-eastern Europe (<ce:cross-refs refid="b0285 b0135 b0090" id="r0080">Tabaku &amp; Meyer 1999, Hobi et al. 2015, Frankovic et al. 2021</ce:cross-refs>). For example, stand structural analyses in the Kyjov beech primeval forest of this study revealed mean gap size to vary between 95 and 260 m<ce:sup loc="post">2</ce:sup> (with a maximum of 4415 m<ce:sup loc="post">2</ce:sup>) during a 10-yr observation period with on average 8–14 % of stand area occupied by gaps (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0075" id="c0250">Feldmann et al. 2018b</ce:cross-ref>). Most gaps are created by the death of single trees, and gap size likely is in most cases too small to induce major SOC losses. In addition, large parts of the forest floor are already covered with tree regeneration in different stages of ontogenetic development at the time of gap formation (<ce:cross-refs refid="b0075 b0080" id="r0085">Feldmann et al. 2018b, Feldmann et al. 2020</ce:cross-refs>). Large natural gaps resembling clear-cuts such as the 8.3 ha-wind throw caused by a severe gale in 2014 in the Havešová primeval forest seem to be very rare events. In contrast to temperate eastern Asia and eastern North America, where severe storms are more common (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0250" id="c0255">Peters 1997</ce:cross-ref>), are the temperate forests of Europe rarely exposed to stand-replacing natural hazards, and SOC accumulation can usually continue for centuries without major interruption. It is therefore plausible that long continuity of forest cover is one important factor that has promoted C enrichment in the soil under our primeval forests. This may change in future, if climate change were to reduce tree health and reduce canopy cover due to forest dieback (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0265" id="c0260">Senf and Seidl 2021</ce:cross-ref>).</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0130" view="all">For forested land, a positive correlation between tree biomass and SOC has been found (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0050" id="c0265">Dean et al. 2017</ce:cross-ref>), which may result from higher litter C input (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0280" id="c0270">Sun et al. 2004</ce:cross-ref>). Large trees could also enhance SOC through elevated soil carbon concentrations directly under the trunk, probably resulting from high root biomass (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0055" id="c0275">Dean et al. 2020</ce:cross-ref>). In our data set, however, a positive biomass − SOC relation did not exist. Even though we found a more than four times larger deadwood amount, a 20% higher wood biomass, and also a 15 % larger SOC stock in the primeval forests compared to the managed forests, we detected no significant relationship between SOC stock and aboveground biomass or deadwood amount across the sampled plots. Similar results were obtained by <ce:cross-ref refid="b0175" id="c0280">Krueger et al. (2017)</ce:cross-ref>. This is plausible from the fact that ANPP and aboveground litter production were similar in our primeval and managed forests (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0095" id="c0285">Glatthorn et al. 2018</ce:cross-ref>), suggesting that the annual C supply to the soil from aboveground litter was not larger in the primeval forests. However, we have no data on root-derived C input into the soil. Several authors have postulated for old-growth forests a higher C input into the soil with dissolved organic carbon (DOC) flux from decaying deadwood (<ce:cross-refs refid="b0045 b0275" id="r0090">Crow et al. 2007, Spears &amp; Lajtha 2004</ce:cross-refs>), which could explain higher SOC stocks in primeval forests. A detailed study on SOC stocks and DOC fluxes in paired managed and unmanaged temperate broadleaf forests, however, did not find evidence for an important role of DOC transfer from deadwood to the soil in the unmanaged stands (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0175" id="c0290">Krueger et al. 2017</ce:cross-ref>). Thus, differences in tree-derived C supply to the soil are an unlikely cause of the observed SOC differences between primeval and managed stands, which would disprove our third hypothesis. Nevertheless, DOC measurements in deadwood-rich primeval forests are needed to better understand the role of large coarse wood debris for SOC accumulation.</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0135" view="all">Our findings suggest that soil chemical differences between primeval and managed forests, which likely are caused by the management, are significantly influencing SOC stocks. The soils under the managed forests had a slightly, but significantly, higher availability of P and base cations (Ca, K, Mg) than the primeval forest soils, even though bedrock and principal soil types were similar in the stand pairs. It appears that tree harvesting and the related soil disturbance have significantly increased the availability of P, Ca, K, and Mg, and have slightly reduced soil acidity. Soil N content did not differ significantly, but soil C/N ratios were narrower in the managed forests mainly due to lower SOC concentrations, suggesting better mineral N supply. Comparing managed and unmanaged beech forests in north-western Spain, <ce:cross-ref refid="b0220" id="c0295">Merino et al. (2008)</ce:cross-ref> found higher extractable P contents in the mineral soil and elevated foliar K and Mg, but not N, contents in the partly cut stands. Since SOC accumulation generally is the higher the lower soil microbial activity (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0010" id="c0300">Alexander 1980</ce:cross-ref>), it is plausible that the somewhat higher P and cation (and N) availability in the managed forests is one of the main causes of the lower SOC stocks of these systems. Moreover, the somewhat wider C/N ratio in the primeval forest soils could have favoured SOC storage, as the potential of soils to store C generally increases with soil C/N ratio (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0015" id="c0305">Averill et al. 2014</ce:cross-ref>). The PCA suggests that topsoil base cation concentrations are a main determinant of SOC stocks in our plots, while P and N availably are less important. We assume that nutrients (especially base cations) contained in foliage and branch biomass are rapidly released after tree harvest, thereby increasing nutrient availability for the re-growing forest and also for soil biota, if the nutrients are not leached with runoff and seepage water. Thus, clear-cutting in the past likely has stimulated nutrient cycling and increased soil fertility in the managed forests through both the supply of relatively nutrient-rich plant debris and higher soil temperatures (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0170" id="c0310">Kreuzweiser et al. 2008</ce:cross-ref>), causing somewhat higher soil biological activity and decomposition rates (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0215" id="c0315">Mayer et al. 2020</ce:cross-ref>).</ce:para>
                  </ce:section>
               </ce:section>
               <ce:section id="s0070" view="all">
                  <ce:label>5</ce:label>
                  <ce:section-title id="st085">Conclusions</ce:section-title>
                  <ce:para id="p0140" view="all">Through comparison with true primeval forests, we found evidence for a lasting effect of forest management on SOC stocks in Slovakian beech forests, even though management intensity is relatively low in this region. This suggests that SOC accumulation must continue well beyond 100 years after clear-cut. Clearly, the statistical significance of our results is limited, which is mainly a consequence of the small number (N = 3) of replicate stands investigated. Complementary studies in other temperate woodlands with remaining primeval forests would be needed to test the broader validity of our findings. As management intensity is usually higher in other regions of Central Europe than in eastern Slovakia, SOC differences between primeval and managed forests could be even greater than reported here. In any case, our results highlight the importance of primeval forests as indispensable reference systems for forest ecological and biogeochemical research.</ce:para>
               </ce:section>
            </ce:sections>
            <ce:conflict-of-interest id="coi005" view="all">
               <ce:section-title id="st095">Declaration of Competing Interest</ce:section-title>
               <ce:para id="p0150" view="all">The authors declare that they have no known competing financial interests or personal relationships that could have appeared to influence the work reported in this paper.</ce:para>
            </ce:conflict-of-interest>
            <ce:acknowledgment id="ak005" view="all">
               <ce:section-title id="st100">Acknowledgements</ce:section-title>
               <ce:para id="p0155" view="all">This study was supported through a grant of the Stemmler Foundation, a member of the Stifterverband für die Deutsche Wissenschaft, to C. Leuschner. This support is gratefully acknowledged. We are also grateful to the Poloniny National Park authority, the local forest administrations and the Ministry of Defence of the Slovak Republic for the permits to conduct the study and for technical support during the field work. Many thanks also to Peter Hajek for support during sample collection and two anonymous reviewers for helpful comments on an earlier draft.</ce:para>
            </ce:acknowledgment>
            <ce:appendices view="all">
               <ce:section view="compact-standard" id="s0080">
